AB The deficit attenuation hypothesis is the proposal that age related
   declines in basic cognitive functions often result in compensatory
   changes in decision making strategies. However, the patterns of
   cognitive changes across the adult life span are complex: Many cognitive
   abilities change across the adult life span while others do not. Some of
   the cognitive changes will be detrimental to decision making, others
   will have no impact and still others may actually improve decision
   making. We illustrate the complexity of the impact of cognition on aging
   and decision making with examples from working and long-term memory and
   use these to suggest boundary conditions for the deficit attenuation
   hypothesis. (C) 2008 Society for Consumer Psychology. Published by
