AB In word-of-mouth marketing, marketers often provide financial rewards
   for referrals. These rewards introduce a financial motive into an
   interaction among friends or acquaintances, which may harm the perceived
   sincerity of the referring customer. We show that this negative effect
   can be mitigated by disclosing the presence of financial motives, but
   also by the activation of a market pricing ('sales') relationship norm.
   However, such a norm has a negative effect on compliance with the
   referral. The effects of relationship norms are strongest when cognitive
   capacity is impaired, which suggests that the influence of relationship
   norms occurs outside the awareness of consumers. Conversely, the impact
   of disclosures is stronger when consumers have full cognitive capacity
   available. (C) 2009 Society for Consumer Psychology. Published by
