   adaptation, where the happiness arising from a positive change erodes
   via two key pathways: diminishing positive emotions and rising
   aspirations. In the U.S., hedonic adaptation encourages overspending and
   indebtedness. The practice of thrift is the wise and efficient use of
   resources, and there are many thrifty proponents and adherents
   throughout history including Socrates, King Solomon, Confucius, Benjamin
