AB Prior research has consistently demonstrated that people are reluctant
   to trade a good they own for an alternative good, particularly when the
   alternative (or "target") represents a substantial departure from the
   "endowment". We demonstrate that the endowment effect can be reduced by
   first making participants consider trading their endowment for an
   intermediate alternative (which shares some characteristics of the
