   on extremeness aversion (i.e., the propensity to avoid extreme options
   in choice situations). The results indicate that extremeness aversion is
   a robust phenomenon: middle options are significantly more often
   selected than other options. However, the strength of this behavioral
   effect exhibits substantial variation (up to three times the average
   magnitude) across methodological decisions: employing price-quality
   tradeoffs, nondurable categories, or binary-trinary choice-set
   comparisons tend to reduce the probability of extremeness aversion among
